Director General Lungisa Fuzile left the Treasury after 19 years of service on Monday. CAPE TOWN - Treasury says it will start interviewing potential replacements for Director-General Lungisa Fuzile this week.Fuzile left the Treasury after 19 years of service on Monday.He resigned after former Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan and his deputy Mcebisi Jonas were fired in President Jacob Zuma's recent Cabinet reshuffle.Deputy Director-General Dondo Mogajane will act in the post until Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba makes a recommendation to Cabinet in the next fortnight.Gigaba's spokesperson Mayihlome Tshwete says: We want to communicate to the South African public that the strong institution, National Treasury, is in good hands. Great work has been done over the last 23 years and it will also be done in the coming years. We are only adding our shoulder to the mandate and work done by the outgoing DG and former ministers. (Edited by Shimoney Regter)